  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1295792173" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1295792173" />
    <a title="Ɗẳɳ  2.☊" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/12058788-2"><img alt="Ɗẳɳ  2.☊" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1643059934p2/12058788.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1295792173?book_show_action=true">Jun 01, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ɗẳɳ  2.☊" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ɗẳɳ  2.☊" href="/user/show/12058788-2">Ɗẳɳ  2.☊</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/19438157-wayward">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12058788-2?shelf=apocalyptic">apocalyptic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/12058788-2?shelf=sci-fi-thriller">sci-fi-thriller</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1295792173" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16324547146975579694"><b>★★★☆☆½</b><br/><br/>Here goes, <b>Pointless Review #955</b> (at the time of posting). But is it specifically this review or any review of <i>Wayward</i> that’s pointless? Probably both! The reason is that I imagine those who’ve read the first book fall into one of only two categories: the ones who enjoyed it and are hungry for more, or the ones who couldn’t get past the shoddy writing and all the plotholes. That being the case, I doubt there’s anything I could say to sway your opinion. And the first book was shrouded in so</span>
  <span id="freeText16324547146975579694" style="display:none"><b>★★★☆☆½</b><br /><br />Here goes, <b>Pointless Review #955</b> (at the time of posting). But is it specifically this review or any review of <i>Wayward</i> that’s pointless? Probably both! The reason is that I imagine those who’ve read the first book fall into one of only two categories: the ones who enjoyed it and are hungry for more, or the ones who couldn’t get past the shoddy writing and all the plotholes. That being the case, I doubt there’s anything I could say to sway your opinion. And the first book was shrouded in so much mystery that I’m not sure it’s even possible to review this book without spoiling things. <br /><br />But, come to think of it, I suppose there’s gotta be a third category of readers as well: the apathetic ones who were mildly intrigued but still undecided as to whether it’s worth reading any more. The mystery has already been revealed, is there any real reason to carry on? I think there is, so that’s the group of readers I’d like to address. <br /><br />First, the good news is that the consistency of the writing is steady. There’s no sudden drop in quality, the story doesn’t begin fall apart, there’s no sophomore slump. If you enjoyed book one, by all means, carry on. <br /><br /><i>Wayward</i> picks up right where <i>Pines</i> left off. There’s actually no discernible gap, just a continuation of a larger tale. As you may know, there’s a new sheriff in town, and in book two we get to ride shotgun. We finally get a chance to peek behind the curtain to see how the other half lives. But will the new guy like what he sees? That’s a good question and one that our sheriff struggles with throughout. Also, like so many second books of trilogies, a large chunk of the tale is devoted to backstories that help to flesh out the main characters and help us gain a better perspective of their motivations.<br /><br />The bad news is that the most compelling part of the first story—that crazy WTF is going on here vibe—is completely gone. The answers have been revealed, so, naturally, some of the luster has worn off. And, without any real mystery, all you’re left with is a sci-fi thriller, which, annoying, ends on a major cliffhanger. So it’ll be hard to finish this without feeling an immediate urge to jump right into the last book. But then all three books are rather short page-turners, so I doubt that will prove to be much of a problem for most people. <br /><br /><b>Bottom line:</b> I think it’s time for all you apathetic <i>Pines</i> readers to jump off that fence and give the series another shot. Carry on, old chap, and I think you’ll like what you see. But, if, for some reason, you’re reading this review before you’ve even tried the series, what the hell are you waiting for! Fun and/or idiotic times await.<br /><br /><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1238569849" rel="nofollow noopener">Pines (Book One)</a>: ★★★☆☆½<br />Wayward (Book Two): ★★★☆☆½ rounded up</span>
  <a data-text-id="16324547146975579694" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


