<div id="review_3804766908" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3804766908" />
    <a title="Trish" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3461034-trish"><img alt="Trish" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1588663568p2/3461034.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3804766908?book_show_action=true">May 19, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Trish" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Trish" href="/user/show/3461034-trish">Trish</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audible Audio " href="/book/show/22522744-wayward">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3804766908" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6686817375012992985">I think I liked the first one better, but this second installment was still rather cool.<br/><br/>The story opens about two weeks after the end of the first book. We finally know what Wayward Pines is: <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[the last town on Earth <a class='jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction'>(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. Yep, we are <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[far into humanity&apos;s future (about 2k years) and Pilcher‘s predictions have come true: the human genome really did degrade. However, there are signs that the creatures humans have mutated into are not mindless killing machines,</span></span>
  <span id="freeText6686817375012992985" style="display:none">I think I liked the first one better, but this second installment was still rather cool.<br /><br />The story opens about two weeks after the end of the first book. We finally know what Wayward Pines is: <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[the last town on Earth <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. Yep, we are <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[far into humanity's future (about 2k years) and Pilcher‘s predictions have come true: the human genome really did degrade. However, there are signs that the creatures humans have mutated into are not mindless killing machines, or at least not anymore. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> The few people <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[saved by Pilcher <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> are living <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[fenced in <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> and unaware of <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[what the hell is going on on the other side of the electrified fence (most don‘t even know about the fence) <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. They are scared into submission and kept under surveillance.<br />Which brings about a few problems because Pilcher can't go on <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[terminating everyone refusing to stay / be integrated (because then he'd run out of people eventually) <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> and, according to him, he can't just tell everyone the truth either. <br />So while the first book was about the mystery itself, the most important aspect (for me) in this 2nd volume was how to go on - because it's not just about survival, it's also about the kind of life you live (quality). And resistance has already started forming, a while ago.<br />Ethan Burke is fully aware now and has become the town's new sheriff. His main goal is to keep his family save and live a nice life. But is that even possible under the circumstances? <br />Then there is Wayward Pines first murder and suddenly we‘re smack in the middle of a whodunnit on top of some disconcerting hints about <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[the creatures outside, their intelligence and cooperation, therefore about the danger the town is in, and it very much reminded me of the reveal in <b>I Am Legend</b> <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. It added some shudder-worthy moments that I had missed since the first volume.<br /><br />We got the background stories of most of the players inside the town, learned about their relationships with one another and, yes, also got confirmation that Pilcher is <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[out of his fucking mind and suffering from a severe god complex - just like all his goons <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. Not really a surprise but in a story with so many turns, it wasn‘t a given either. I liked the encroaching darkness, that the idyllic small-town facade made way for the ugliness underneath.<br /><br />Still, there were also a few things that were too over-the-top for me. They weren‘t entirely impossible, but considering how certain key characters had been introduced, it didn‘t fit too well. Or maybe I just hated it. *shrugs* <br />Not that that means the book wasn‘t written as wonderfully as the first - the quality was as high as expected/hoped. And even my complaint about a certain someone supposedly being important and yet only background decoration turned out to have been done this way for a reason.<br /><br />On to the conclusion!</span>
  <a data-text-id="6686817375012992985" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


